Clonality and the evolution of complex multi-cellularity

This script re-creates the analyses of Fisher et al 2013 using this dataset. As this dataset is built on the data from that study (with the addition of a small number of plants), then the results should be v. similar.

2 Recreating results in Fisher without phylogeny

As practise for analyses of germline data.

2.1 is clonal group formation more likely to produce obligate multi-cellularity?

2.1.1 eyeball the data

Summary table to eyeball results:

summary<- df %>%
  group_by(Obligate_or_facultative) %>%
  count()#summary table just to check that the results kinda fit

print(summary)

2.1.2 defining the model

Have defined a v. simple, pretty non-informative prior (makes everything run faster). As a default, brms has flat prior, but defining a simple prior makes things run a bit quicker.

get_prior(log(cell_number) ~ 0 + clonal, family=gaussian(), data = df) #what priors do we need to define?
Rows containing NAs were excluded from the model.
                 prior class             coef group resp dpar nlpar bound       source
                (flat)     b                                                   default
                (flat)     b     clonalclonal                             (vectorized)
                (flat)     b clonalnonMclonal                             (vectorized)
 student_t(3, 0, 11.1) sigma                                                   default
#fit the model 
fit_obl<-
  brm(data = df,
      family=bernoulli(link = 'logit'), # family of model
      formula = Obligate_or_facultative ~ 0 + clonal,  #formula, the 0 means that there are estimates for both clonal and non-clonal, rather than relative to each other
      iter = 600000, warmup = 10000, chains = 5,thin = 100, cores = 5, #chain settings
      prior = prior(normal(0, 10), "b"), #defining the priors- for things in 'class b' set this prior. (can also use get_priors() and set_priors() fucncitons) 
      file = 'fits/obligate' )

2.3 Cell types

2.3.1 eyeball the data

df %>%

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

2.3.2 define the model

This model has scaled, log transforemed cell number as an explanatory variable (as we expect more cells to lead to more cell types)

fit_type<-
  brm(data = df,
      family=poisson(),
      formula = cell_types ~ 0 + clonal + scale(log(cell_number)),
      iter = 600000, warmup = 100000, chains = 5, thin = 1000, cores = 5,
      prior = prior(normal(0, 10), "b"), file = 'fits/cell_type')

3 Results with phylogeny included

#read in phylogeny
phylo<- ape::read.tree('data/phylogeny_all.txt')
#subset df above with just those that are in the tree (note some missing)
names_in_tree<- read.csv('data/phylogeny_species_names_in_tree.csv')
names_in_tree$ott_id<- paste('ott',names_in_tree$ott_id, sep = '')
#phylo$tip.label %in% names_in_tree$ott_id #to check whether they're all present
names_in_tree<- subset(names_in_tree, names_in_tree$ott_id %in% phylo$tip.label)
#which species in the table are in the tree
df$species.updated.rotl<- tolower(df$species.updated.rotl)
df<- subset(df, tolower(df$species.updated.rotl) %in% tolower(names_in_tree$search_string))
#give them the ids in a column sot hat brms can match it up
df$species_id<- names_in_tree$ott_id

Covariance matrix produced using branch lengths of 1 (as in Fisher et al)

# set branch lengths to 1 for covariance matrix
phylo_1b <- compute.brlen(phylo, 1)
#create covariance matrix
CovarMatrix <- ape::vcv.phylo(phylo_1b)
